      <body>
         <head>To <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers0025.xml"/>William Allwood</persName><note
               place="foot" n="1">While the address is not visible, <persName><ptr
                     target="/persons/pers0025.xml"/>William Allwood</persName> had been assigned to
               serve the <placeName>York</placeName> circuit the previous month with <persName><ptr
                     target="/persons/pers1439.xml"/>Thomas Mitchell</persName> and <persName><ptr
                     target="/persons/pers2038.xml"/>Thomas Tobias</persName> (see 10:287 in this
               edn.), one of Wesley&apos;s <seg ana="itinerancy">itinerant preachers</seg> on the
                  <placeName>York</placeName> &apos;Round&apos; or circuit (see 21:206, n. 9 in this
               edn.) <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> often spelled
                     <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers0025.xml"/>his</persName> last name
                     &apos;<persName><ptr target="/persons/pers0025.xml"/>Alwood</persName>&apos;,
               but <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers0025.xml"/>his</persName> own signature
               included the second &apos;l&apos;.</note></head>
         <opener><placeName>Bristol</placeName><lb/><date when="1758-09-13">September 13,
               1758</date><lb/><lb/>
            <salute>My Dear Brother,</salute>
         </opener>
         <p>Enquire <hi rend="italic">why</hi> brother <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers0793.xml"
               />Gibbs</persName><note place="foot" n="2">This is apparently <persName><ptr
                     target="/persons/pers0793.xml"/>John Gibbs</persName>, who was accepted as an
                  <seg ana="itinerancy">itinerant</seg> at the <date when="1758-08">August
                  1758</date> Conference (see 10:282 in this edn.); perhaps <persName><ptr
                     target="/persons/pers0793.xml"/>he</persName> had been preaching in
                  <placeName>York</placeName> previously, or maybe <persName><ptr
                     target="/persons/pers0793.xml"/>he</persName> stayed in
                  <placeName>York</placeName> even though <persName><ptr
                     target="/persons/pers0793.xml"/>he</persName> was assigned by Conference to
                  <placeName>Cornwall</placeName> (see 10:286 in this edn. and <persName><ptr
                     target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s letter to <persName><ptr
                     target="/persons/pers0025.xml"/>Allwood</persName> on <date when="1758-10-15"
                  >Oct. 15, 1758</date>)</note> was not liked at those places and tell
                  <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers0793.xml"/>him</persName> frankly what has
            been amiss. Write again and hasten brother <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2038.xml"
               />Tobias</persName>.<note place="foot" n="3"><persName><ptr
                     target="/persons/pers2038.xml"/>Thomas Tobias</persName> (d. <date when="1767"
                  >1767</date>) was a native of <placeName>Wales</placeName> who appears in the
               Minutes as a <seg ana="itinerancy">traveling preacher</seg> in <date when="1755"
                  >1755</date> (10:272 in this edn.) and served until <persName><ptr
                     target="/persons/pers2038.xml"/>his</persName> death in early <date when="1767"
                  >1767</date>. See Atmore, <hi rend="italic">Memorial</hi>, 428–30.</note>
            <placeName>Lincolnshire</placeName> is now fully supplied without <persName><ptr
                  target="/persons/pers2038.xml"/>him</persName>.</p>
         <p><persName><ptr target="/persons/pers1439.xml"/>Thomas Mitchell</persName><note
               place="foot" n="4">On <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers1439.xml"/>Thomas
                  Mitchell</persName>, see 26:474 in this edn.</note> is fast in
               <placeName>Sussex</placeName> as yet; I have letter upon letter to desire
                  <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers1439.xml"/>he</persName> may not leave it, and
            I suppose <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers1439.xml"/>he</persName> will not stir
            from thence till I &lt;go<note place="foot" n="5">A small portion of the manuscript is
               torn away, but can be reconstructed in the two lines affected.</note>&gt; myself and
            fetch <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers1439.xml"/>him</persName>.</p>
         <p>I &lt;know&gt; no reason at all why you should not feel always what you felt then. The
            gifts of God are all without repentance on <hi rend="italic">his</hi> part. He is
            willing to give always what he gives once, and what more than you feel, <persName><ptr
                  target="/persons/pers0909.xml"/>Ruth Hall</persName><note place="foot" n="6">This
               is <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s first mention
               of Mrs. <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers0909.xml"/>Ruth Hall</persName> (maiden
               name unknown). <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers0909.xml"/>She</persName> was born
               in <placeName>Woolley, Yorkshire</placeName> in <date when="1732">1732</date>,
               converted in <placeName>York</placeName> in <date when="1752">1752</date>, married in
                  <date when="1753">1753</date>, and claimed entire sanctification in <date
                  when="1757">1757</date>. <persName><ptr target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                  />JW</persName> carried on extensive correspondence with <persName><ptr
                     target="/persons/pers0909.xml"/>her</persName> between <date from="1759"
                  to="1762">1759 and 1762</date>, though only his published transcriptions of her
               letters survive. See &apos;A Short Account of <persName><ptr
                     target="/persons/pers0909.xml"/>Ruth Hall</persName>&apos;, <hi rend="italic"
                  >AM</hi> 4 (<date when="1781">1781</date>): 477–80.</note> experiences—it is all
            for <hi rend="italic">you</hi>. Only be not afraid of knowing yourself, of seeing the
            inbred monster&apos;s face. I am, with love to her and all our friends,</p>
         <closer><signed>Your affectionate brother,<lb/><persName>J. Wesley</persName></signed></closer>
      </body>
